\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 5. R. nigrum} L.,{\i  Sp. Pl. }201 (1753). Plant 1-2 m. Leaves up to 10 cm wide, glabrous above, slightly pubescent and with numerous sessile, aromatic glands beneath. Racemes drooping. Flowers campanulate, reddish- or brownish-green. Sepals oblong, recurved, pubescent; petals smaller, erect, whitish. Fruit up to 12 mm in diameter, black, sweetish and aromatic. 2n = 16.{\i  Damp woods. Most of Europe, except the Mediterranean region; native certainly in C. & E. Europe; cultivated for its fruits} ({\i Black Currants}), {\i and widely naturalized in the west, where its native limits are hard to ascertain.} *Au *Be *Br Bu *Cz *Da Fe Ga Ge *Ho *Hu It Ju *No Po Rm Rs(N, B, C, W, E) Su [Co Hb He].
