\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. P. crassifolium} Banks & Solander ex A. Cunn., {\i Ann. Nat. Hist.}{\b  4}: 106 (1839). An erect shrub or small tree up to 10 m, with black bark and a subfastigiate crown. Leaves 5-8 × 2-3 cm obovate-oblong to oblong, obtuse to subacute, with revolute margins, dark green above and white-tomentose beneath, very coriaceous. Flowers in few-flowered umbellate cymes. Petals blackish-purple, oblong. Capsule 12-20 mm, subglobose, white-tomentose, with 3 or 4 woody valves.{\i  Cultivated for ornament and shelter in parts of W. Europe; naturalized in S.W. England} ({\i Isles of Scilly}). [Br.] ({\i New Zealand}.)
